lt is under this last aspect alone that we have now to speak of the works of Cicero. We must remember that he figured to after ages as the Roman Plato ². lt was he alone who en· deavoured, as his great predecessor had done, to wed strength of reason to beauty of style, and once more to make the dialogue the vehicle of philosophical instruction.
